Its immense smooth trunk
makes its high branches above

36:57.280 --> 36:59.800
a safe place to nest,

36:59.800 --> 37:01.440
but over the years,

37:01.440 --> 37:04.000
this has created
a major problem for the tree.

37:09.160 --> 37:12.120
After feeding, the starlings
return to the nest

37:12.120 --> 37:14.280
to digest their food,

37:14.280 --> 37:16.880
with inevitable consequences.

37:22.160 --> 37:23.600
Every year,

37:23.600 --> 37:27.720
they produce almost a quarter
of a ton of droppings.

37:30.880 --> 37:33.160
The toxic chemicals
they contain

37:33.160 --> 37:36.440
create a dead zone that
completely surrounds the tree.

37:44.160 --> 37:47.200
The toxins are absorbed
by its roots

37:47.200 --> 37:50.600
and travel up through the trunk
and into every leaf.

38:06.080 --> 38:08.880
Branch by branch,

38:08.880 --> 38:11.480
the tree is slowly dying.

38:14.600 --> 38:17.920
It has become a victim
of its own success.

38:19.840 --> 38:21.520
It has been poisoned.

38:29.120 --> 38:31.600
Now a new battle begins...

38:34.080 --> 38:36.800
..one to claim the tree's
dead body

38:36.800 --> 38:40.320
and the vast amount of nutrients
that it contains.

38:42.040 --> 38:45.120
It's a battle that is fought
throughout the natural world...

38:46.400 --> 38:48.480
..involving a group
of organisms

38:48.480 --> 38:49.960
that we rarely notice.

38:52.560 --> 38:56.160
Here, on the floor
of a tropical rainforest,

38:56.160 --> 38:58.960
it's dark, it's humid

38:58.960 --> 39:00.640
and it's hot -

39:00.640 --> 39:04.040
ideal conditions for fungi.

39:04.040 --> 39:07.920
We normally think of fungi
as things like this.

39:07.920 --> 39:10.320
Mushrooms of one kind
or another.

39:10.320 --> 39:12.760
But these are just
the fruiting bodies.

39:15.440 --> 39:17.920
They exist for most of the time

39:17.920 --> 39:20.520
hidden in the leaf litter
and the earth

39:20.520 --> 39:22.840
as a network
of fine white threads.

39:25.160 --> 39:29.720
The threads of competing fungi
envelop their victim's body,

39:29.720 --> 39:33.440
releasing enzymes which digest
the tree's tissues

39:33.440 --> 39:35.960
and unlock the nutrients within.

39:38.600 --> 39:42.120
There a million or so
different species of fungi

39:42.120 --> 39:44.400
in the tropics.

39:44.400 --> 39:47.640
Some feed on dead plants.

39:47.640 --> 39:49.400
Others eat them alive.

39:51.000 --> 39:55.480
And some reveal their existence
in an eerily beautiful way.

40:05.640 --> 40:07.840
In Africa, in the Congo,

40:07.840 --> 40:10.760
this is known
as chimpanzee fire.

40:16.520 --> 40:19.480
The mysterious
bioluminescent glow

40:19.480 --> 40:23.120
becomes brighter as the fungus
digests the tree.

40:28.560 --> 40:30.800
When fungi have fed
sufficiently,

40:30.800 --> 40:33.240
they develop
their reproductive organs.

41:02.600 --> 41:06.720
Each can produce
literally billions of spores...

41:09.000 --> 41:10.560
..the tiny particles

41:10.560 --> 41:12.800
that carry the species'
genetic blueprint.

41:15.800 --> 41:17.720
Each spore like this

41:17.720 --> 41:20.240
has the potential
to kill a tree.

41:43.240 --> 41:45.000
The spores are so light

41:45.000 --> 41:47.680
they can be carried by
the slightest air currents.

41:57.280 --> 41:59.120
At least a billion

41:59.120 --> 42:02.080
float above every square metre
of rainforest.

42:12.040 --> 42:15.200
Recently, it has been
discovered that these spores

42:15.200 --> 42:18.600
do far more than just
bring death and decay.

42:21.000 --> 42:24.440
They are, in fact,
at the very centre

42:24.440 --> 42:27.040
of the rainforest's
life support system.

42:35.240 --> 42:36.960
High in the humid air,

42:36.960 --> 42:39.840
the spores combine
with molecules of water.

42:53.720 --> 42:56.640
Gradually,
they collect into droplets,

42:56.640 --> 42:59.840
which,
when they are heavy enough, fall...

43:02.280 --> 43:03.760
..as rain.

43:43.000 --> 43:46.880
Over two-and-a-half metres
of rain falls every year

43:46.880 --> 43:48.680
in a rainforest.

43:56.000 --> 43:59.440
And in the centre
of almost every raindrop,

43:59.440 --> 44:01.200
there is a fungal spore.

44:16.680 --> 44:19.800
The world's rainforests
are the richest

44:19.800 --> 44:22.960
and most dynamic environments
on Earth,

44:22.960 --> 44:26.840
built on complex connections
and relationships.

44:30.680 --> 44:32.640
But these connections,

44:32.640 --> 44:35.280
competitive or collaborative,

44:35.280 --> 44:37.840
are now becoming
increasingly fragile.

44:53.800 --> 44:58.080
When Charles Darwin was exploring
the tropical world

44:58.080 --> 45:00.320
nearly 200 years ago,

45:00.320 --> 45:03.480
he wrote this in his diary.

45:03.480 --> 45:08.200
"Among the scenes which are
deeply impressed on my mind,

45:08.200 --> 45:11.520
"none exceed in sublimity

45:11.520 --> 45:16.840
"the primeval forests
undefaced by the hand of man."

45:18.520 --> 45:21.440
He would struggle to find
such a place today.

45:36.520 --> 45:41.080
Today, 70% of all the world's
rainforest plants

45:41.080 --> 45:44.320
grow within a mile of a road
or a clearing

45:44.320 --> 45:47.520
that we have cut into the forest...

45:50.920 --> 45:54.120
..and this is creating
new battlefields

45:54.120 --> 45:55.840
in the tropical world.

45:58.080 --> 46:01.640
Alien armies of identical
cultivated plants

46:01.640 --> 46:05.480
now stand where thousands
of different species once grew.

46:14.400 --> 46:17.640
We have planted
vast regiments of crops

46:17.640 --> 46:20.160
in order to provide ourselves

46:20.160 --> 46:22.360
with food
and other commodities...

46:24.400 --> 46:27.000
..and the ancient forest
has been reduced

46:27.000 --> 46:29.720
to ever fewer isolated fragments.

46:34.360 --> 46:36.240
All, however, is not lost.

46:37.880 --> 46:40.880
The fragments
can still be sanctuaries,

46:40.880 --> 46:44.080
keeping alive the intimate
relationships within them.

46:46.520 --> 46:49.600
Their size is
nonetheless critical.

46:59.040 --> 47:01.960
This is the seven-hour flower.

47:13.360 --> 47:17.040
This plant produces its flowers
at night.

47:17.040 --> 47:19.800
They open about six o'clock,

47:19.800 --> 47:24.440
and each blossom only lasts
that night.

47:24.440 --> 47:27.080
It opens for about seven hours

47:27.080 --> 47:29.520
and then it dies.

47:29.520 --> 47:32.120
But during that time,
it provides food

47:32.120 --> 47:33.840
for one particular animal.

47:35.200 --> 47:36.760
A bat.

47:36.760 --> 47:38.160
And here it is!

47:56.800 --> 47:59.840
During the seven-hour flower's
flowering season...

48:01.520 --> 48:04.880
..Underwood's bat feeds
almost exclusively on its nectar.

48:07.040 --> 48:09.680
It is the plant's
primary pollinator.

48:14.160 --> 48:16.280
It might seem that this is

48:16.280 --> 48:19.200
a fairly evenly balanced
relationship,

48:19.200 --> 48:20.560
but not so.

48:21.880 --> 48:26.120
The bat likes this nectar
because it's sweet,

48:26.120 --> 48:29.520
but it's not very nourishing.

48:29.520 --> 48:32.480
So the bat must visit
hundreds of flowers a night...

48:35.400 --> 48:37.600
..and it pollinates them
as if feeds.

48:45.400 --> 48:48.880
But if a patch of forest
becomes too small,

48:48.880 --> 48:50.680
with too few flowers,

48:50.680 --> 48:52.800
the bats will disappear,

48:52.800 --> 48:56.280
and without the bats,
the flowers can't reproduce

48:56.280 --> 48:57.920
and will soon die out.

49:00.400 --> 49:02.120
The partnership is broken.

49:12.560 --> 49:17.040
Life in the forest depends on
countless close relationships,

49:17.040 --> 49:19.800
but they are increasingly
under threat

49:19.800 --> 49:23.440
as forests become more fragmented.

49:23.440 --> 49:24.920
The solution, of course,

49:24.920 --> 49:27.640
is to join these remaining
fragments together again.

49:28.880 --> 49:32.000
30 years ago,
I came to this exact spot.

49:33.840 --> 49:35.720
This land belonged to

49:35.720 --> 49:37.840
a scientific research
establishment

49:37.840 --> 49:41.520
and it was covered with grass
being grazed by cattle.

49:41.520 --> 49:44.520
The scientists
got rid of the cattle

49:44.520 --> 49:47.800
and allowed nature
to take its course.

49:47.800 --> 49:49.560
Just look at it now!

49:58.920 --> 50:01.880
This new forest
has become a bridge

50:01.880 --> 50:04.840
that connects several fragments,

50:04.840 --> 50:09.280
allowing plants and animals
to both renew old connections

50:09.280 --> 50:11.120
and create fresh ones.

50:22.840 --> 50:26.320
Of course,
we urgently need to protect

50:26.320 --> 50:28.480
what healthy forests still remain.

50:33.040 --> 50:34.640
But looking forward,

50:34.640 --> 50:38.000
we must take what may well be
our last chance

50:38.000 --> 50:40.520
to re-establish
the lost rainforest...

50:44.320 --> 50:48.120
..and help the tropical world
to heal itself.

50:50.960 --> 50:55.480
It will take the co-operation
of nations around the world,

50:55.480 --> 50:58.760
but it is the only way in which
we'll be able to

50:58.760 --> 51:02.240
preserve the treasures
of the tropical rainforest

51:02.240 --> 51:04.560
for future generations.

51:04.560 --> 51:06.600
And with it,

51:06.600 --> 51:10.200
ultimately protect all life
on this,

51:10.200 --> 51:13.000
our green planet.

51:29.120 --> 51:32.840
The aim of The Green Planet team
was to take the viewer

51:32.840 --> 51:35.640
into the world of plants,
so that it could be seen

51:35.640 --> 51:37.400
from the plants' perspective

51:37.400 --> 51:39.600
in a way that had not been
possible till now.

51:41.840 --> 51:45.040
That meant developing
an entirely new camera system.

51:51.560 --> 51:54.440
And this is the game-changer -

51:54.440 --> 51:57.480
a specially designed
robot camera

51:57.480 --> 52:00.120
that we affectionately call
"the Triffid".

52:05.080 --> 52:08.240
The Triffid started life
in the garage of an American

52:08.240 --> 52:11.040
ex-military engineer,
Chris Field.

52:11.040 --> 52:12.520
I'd seen quite a few of these

52:12.520 --> 52:14.720
Planet Earth style
documentaries,

52:14.720 --> 52:16.520
and they always absolutely
blew my mind,

52:16.520 --> 52:19.840
especially the botanic time-lapse
really spoke to me.

52:19.840 --> 52:22.760
In his spare time,
Chris spent a decade

52:22.760 --> 52:25.240
building elaborate
motion-controlled

52:25.240 --> 52:27.400
time-lapse camera rigs

52:27.400 --> 52:30.960
and teaching himself
how to film plants.

52:30.960 --> 52:34.840
Plants often behave like
animals in so many ways,

52:34.840 --> 52:37.480
and being able to see it
through time-lapse is one thing

52:37.480 --> 52:40.720
but using the motion-control
brings you into that timescale.

52:45.480 --> 52:47.560
We could really see the potential

52:47.560 --> 52:49.560
in how we could use
this sort of movement

52:49.560 --> 52:51.560
to bring plants alive

52:51.560 --> 52:54.040
and film them in the same way
that we film animals.

52:56.320 --> 52:58.240
Soon, Chris joins the team

52:58.240 --> 53:00.840
in a quiet corner
of the Devon countryside

53:00.840 --> 53:03.800
and the robot army begins
to take shape.

53:05.560 --> 53:08.080
After 40 years
of filming time-lapse,

53:08.080 --> 53:11.440
these rigs have opened up
a whole new world for us.

53:12.720 --> 53:15.840
So, it'll be like
hovering around something

53:15.840 --> 53:18.520
with a drone or helicopter,
but in a time-lapse speed.

53:20.600 --> 53:24.040
The holy grail for us is being
able to take this technology

53:24.040 --> 53:27.400
out into the wild, try and get
the same sorts of dynamic moves

53:27.400 --> 53:30.120
in some of the most extreme
environments in the world.

53:32.800 --> 53:34.280
So, what we needed to do

53:34.280 --> 53:37.240
was to develop this technology
even further.

53:37.240 --> 53:39.760
Six months later,
the Triffid is born...

53:42.520 --> 53:47.400
..and with slight trepidation,
they hand me the controls.

53:47.400 --> 53:50.360
That makes it go away.

53:50.360 --> 53:53.160
And this makes it come back.

53:53.160 --> 53:55.760
And this sends it up.

53:59.240 --> 54:00.440
Ooh!

54:01.680 --> 54:04.440
I think I'd better hand it over
to the experts.

54:06.520 --> 54:09.080
Now it's time to put
this new member of the team

54:09.080 --> 54:10.800
properly through its paces.

54:13.480 --> 54:16.280
The aim here is for Ollie
to find a target, aim for it

54:16.280 --> 54:18.720
and fly through it,
as if he is a tiny fly

54:18.720 --> 54:21.120
going through a hole in a leaf.

54:21.120 --> 54:23.360
Easier said than done.

54:23.360 --> 54:25.600
Oops!
I'm trying to find a target.

54:27.320 --> 54:31.240
Whether the kit's going to
stand up to that sort of use

54:31.240 --> 54:34.040
and the abuse that we throw
at most pieces of kit

54:34.040 --> 54:35.600
has yet to be seen.

54:35.600 --> 54:39.160
In the studio, it seems to be
working pretty well.

54:39.160 --> 54:41.760
But this is only
a dress rehearsal.

54:41.760 --> 54:44.400
It's time for the Triffid
to face the challenges

54:44.400 --> 54:46.840
of the Costa Rican rainforest,

54:46.840 --> 54:48.760
and leafcutter ants.

54:55.400 --> 54:58.720
We want to film their journey
all the way

54:58.720 --> 55:02.200
down the trunk
and along this buttress root

55:02.200 --> 55:03.680
and down to their nest.

55:05.400 --> 55:07.720
The team and the Triffid
need several days

55:07.720 --> 55:09.200
of dry weather,

55:09.200 --> 55:11.800
but a storm can hit
at any moment...

55:13.000 --> 55:15.560
..and rain is one thing
the Triffid does not like.

55:17.920 --> 55:20.160
The conditions
that we're working in now

55:20.160 --> 55:22.720
are a little bit more
challenging than the studio.

55:24.520 --> 55:27.080
All the ground is really bumpy.

55:27.080 --> 55:29.080
We've got loads of plants
in the way.

55:29.080 --> 55:31.360
I know we're making a series
about plants,

55:31.360 --> 55:33.920
but sometimes they're
a complete pain in the neck!

55:36.080 --> 55:38.520
The Triffid needs to be
programmed

55:38.520 --> 55:42.320
to capture images from 7,000
different camera positions

55:42.320 --> 55:43.640
on the ants' trail.

55:46.120 --> 55:48.280
Just one drop of rain
on the lens,

55:48.280 --> 55:49.480
or a wobble,

55:49.480 --> 55:52.680
and the whole process
will have to start again.

55:52.680 --> 55:55.560
I think this is when
we're going to find out

55:55.560 --> 55:58.080
if our ambition
outweighs our ability.

56:01.800 --> 56:04.120
For the crew,
the ambition is certainly high.

56:07.640 --> 56:10.480
Fortunately, it's all down
to the Triffid now.

56:20.320 --> 56:23.560
We've been filming the ants
with the Triffid

56:23.560 --> 56:27.240
for eight days now,
and we're on our third set-up.

56:27.240 --> 56:29.240
It's pretty slow going.

56:30.320 --> 56:33.480
While the Triffid seems to be
handling the pressure well,

56:33.480 --> 56:37.200
for the crew, trying to take
a tree's-eye view of ants

56:37.200 --> 56:39.520
is turning into
a bit of a nightmare.

56:41.400 --> 56:45.520
Wake up, film ants,
go to sleep, dream of ants.

56:45.520 --> 56:48.640
Wake up, film ants, sleep,
dream of ants.

56:48.640 --> 56:50.400
Wake up, film ants,

56:50.400 --> 56:53.120
go to sleep, dream of ants.

56:56.360 --> 56:58.160
After two weeks in the jungle,

56:58.160 --> 57:01.320
ambition and ability
finally come together,

57:01.320 --> 57:03.600
for the Triffid, at least.

57:03.600 --> 57:06.240
Thousands of individual images

57:06.240 --> 57:08.680
creating a single
extraordinary time-lapse...

57:11.560 --> 57:14.000
..one that follows
a river of leaves

57:14.000 --> 57:16.840
across the jungle floor
from a unique perspective.

57:21.920 --> 57:24.600
For the Triffid,
this was just the beginning.

57:27.200 --> 57:29.080
Take a bow, Triffid.

57:34.920 --> 57:37.840
Next time on The Green Planet...

57:37.840 --> 57:40.600
..the wonder of water worlds...

57:42.960 --> 57:45.240
..where plants hunt...

57:46.920 --> 57:48.560
..go on the move...

57:49.920 --> 57:51.040
..fight...

57:52.720 --> 57:54.920
..and create the air we breathe.

57:57.920 --> 58:01.360
The Open University
have produced a poster

58:01.360 --> 58:06.040
that explores the vital role
that plants have for our planet.

58:06.040 --> 58:08.200
To order your free copy, call...

58:12.120 --> 58:13.480
..or go to...

58:18.000 --> 58:20.800
..and follow the links
to The Open University.
